    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_2082477370" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2082477370" />
    <a title="Amanda Kratz" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/65751558-amanda-kratz"><img alt="Amanda Kratz" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1492453986p2/65751558.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2082477370?book_show_action=true">Sep 02, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amanda Kratz" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amanda Kratz" href="/user/show/65751558-amanda-kratz">Amanda Kratz</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/65751558-amanda-kratz?shelf=2017-dead-and-unread-book-club">2017-dead-and-unread-book-club</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2082477370" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11158609217148944742">Book club read<br/><br/>Rating 2.5 - rounding down<br/><br/>Published in 1974 the Mote in God&apos;s eye was considered one of the best science fiction works of the time by Robert Heinlein (StarShip Troopers). The book was nominated for the Hugo, Nebula, and Locust awards for best sci-fi book. <br/><br/>I really struggled getting into the first part of this book. I kept falling asleep when trying to read it. It reads like a text book at points. When we finally get more of the aliens (Moties) it starts to pick up and was much more</span>
  <span id="freeText11158609217148944742" style="display:none">Book club read<br /><br />Rating 2.5 - rounding down<br /><br />Published in 1974 the Mote in God's eye was considered one of the best science fiction works of the time by Robert Heinlein (StarShip Troopers). The book was nominated for the Hugo, Nebula, and Locust awards for best sci-fi book. <br /><br />I really struggled getting into the first part of this book. I kept falling asleep when trying to read it. It reads like a text book at points. When we finally get more of the aliens (Moties) it starts to pick up and was much more enjoyable. There is still tons of military gobbledygook and I honestly felt like I was being debriefed at points, but it was better than the opening.<br /><br />I know that when this book was written the authors had spent a lot of time researching the space program and everything represented with ships was the most interesting and theoretical technology that could be realistically achieved. However with today's advancements some of the stuff conceived just sounds silly. This is supposed to be 1000 years in the future. Nothing seems that advanced other than the ability to travel in space itself and even then the author is constantly talking about the "gees" the ship is pulling. While that is realistic you would think there would be advancements that would help negate the effect on the human body. The authors go into such painstaking details of how the ships work and the technology but fails to answer some really basic points like where do they keep getting all these fresh cabbages? I had to laugh when they discussed the pocket computers. (They are more or less a tablet from today's current age)<br /><br />As a female reader I really feel a sexist vibe from the author. Women aren't allowed in the Navy so the crew is all male. This is 1000 years in the future and they treat women as fragile flowers that might wilt. We have 1 female human character who tells us from the get go she talks too much for a lady. We are also told that she is unusual really she should be waiting at home to get married. 😒. The disgust of the humans when they realize the aliens allow their female to preform hazardous tasks. A woman is a spinster if she isn't married by 27. No proper woman uses/needs birth control. Pregnant human women are useless, etc etc. There are many things that annoyed me about this aspect of the book. I know it is likely a product of the era that the author grew up in, but come on you had Star Trek by then. (Also there is a Scottish engineer and huge trouble with tribbles vibe)<br /><br />The moties are an interesting race and I. think once you actually get into the story the culture/world building is interesting. However I really really hated trudging through those opening 10 chapters to get to it. I feel like you could skip large parts of the book and not miss anything. <br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11158609217148944742" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


